<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 13:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2a5ea550630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>13.</label.designator><headtext>Weight and Sufficiency of Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7219dc4682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>13:8.</label.designator><headtext>Uncontroverted evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Historically, Georgia courts have allowed the jury to disregard direct and positive testimony by an unimpeached witness, which is not inherently improbable, incredible or unreasonable and which is not contradicted.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bea371074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] This rule was approved by the Georgia Supreme Court[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea371174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] and has been cited in a number of civil cases.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bea5e2074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><?page no="462"?><bos/><paratext>However, the Georgia Court of Appeals refused to follow this rule in a criminal case, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2008764063" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad2659274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>State v. Brown</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea5e2174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] and followed the majority holding in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad301d274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Tate v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea5e2274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] instead. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad3c52274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Tate</ital></cite.query>, the Georgia Supreme Court held, <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“Credibility of witnesses and the weight to be given their testimony is a decision-making power that lies solely with the trier of fact. <eos/><bos/>The trier of fact is not obligated to believe a witness even if the testimony is uncontradicted and may accept or reject any portion of the testimony.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea5e2374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] The Court further noted <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“a rational trier of fact can choose to reject even ‘undisputed’ testimony if that fact finder believes that witness&apos;s testimony to be unreliable. <eos/><bos/>Factors such as demeanor, contradictory or inconsistent statements and evidence that [a witness] had ‘ulterior motives’ can all lead a finder of fact to disregard testimony.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea853074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] The dissent in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad599e274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Tate</ital></cite.query> disagreed on this point, quoting the contrary rule.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bea853174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] However, as noted by the Georgia Court of Appeals in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2004700557" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad65d3274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>State v. Hester</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea853274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>] <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“[t]here is a difference in arbitrarily or capriciously disregarding testimony and in <ital>disbelieving</ital> it upon a consideration of all circumstances arising from the evidence.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0004"/> <begin.quote ID="QT_0005"/>“The majority opinion in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad7208274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Tate</ital></cite.query> makes it clear, at least in criminal cases, that the trier of fact may disbelieve evidence, even if it is uncontradicted and unimpeached.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0005"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7bea853374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad7e3d274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Tate</ital></cite.query> and its progeny dealt with uncontroverted evidence by a state witness in a criminal prosecution.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7bea853474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference><?page no="463"?>] The contrary rule may still apply in criminal cases based solely on circumstantial evidence when the unimpeached and uncontradicted testimony is that of defense witnesses and in civil cases.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7beaac4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">12</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Regardless, the credibility of evidence is solely a matter for the jury. <eos/><bos/>Thus, if there is any contradiction or other factor (such as bias) which the jury can consider about the credit of the witness, the jury may disbelieve him altogether.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7beaac4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">13</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1979138678" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ada7be274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Wilson v. Professional Ins. Corp.</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7beaac4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">14</footnote.reference>] the court held that the jury may <begin.quote ID="QT_0008"/>“discard the opinion of experts entirely”<end.quote refid="QT_0008"/> and may do so “without rhyme or reason.”<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, on appeal, the appellate court will apply a de novo review of the evidence in reviewing a motion to suppress where the evidence is uncontroverted and there is no issue with the credibility of the witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7beaac4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">15</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7bea371074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1939106337" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I3ad01ba274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Lankford v. Holton, 187 Ga. 94, 102, 200 S.E. 243 (1938)</cite.query>, stating: <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“Direct and positive testimony, as distinguished from testimony circumstantial, opinionative, or actually negative in character, which is given by an unimpeached witness as to the existence of a fact apparently within his own knowledge, which is not in itself incredible, impossible, or inherently improbable, and which is not contradicted directly or by proof of facts or circumstances that could be taken as incompatible with such testimony, cannot be arbitrarily rejected by a jury or other trier of the facts upon the mere surmise that it perhaps might not be in accord with the truth.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea371174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1978132247" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad090d274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Nesbit v. Nesbit, 241 Ga. 351, 245 S.E.2d 303 (1978)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad090d574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><?page no="462"?>Tate v. State, 264 Ga. 53, 59, 440 S.E.2d 646 (1994)</cite.query> (Carley, J., dissenting.).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea5e2074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1901011718" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I3ad1060274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Western &amp; A.R. Co. v. Beason, 112 Ga. 553, 37 S.E. 863 (1901)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1939106337" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I3ad1060574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Lankford v. Holton, 187 Ga. 94, 200 S.E. 243 (1938)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1944104190" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad1060874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Myers v. Phillips, 197 Ga. 536, 29 S.E.2d 700 (1944)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1960123768" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad1060b74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Goldstein v. Drexler, 102 Ga. App. 90, 115 S.E.2d 744 (1960)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1972129051" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad1a24274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Cochran v. Lynch, 126 Ga. App. 866, 192 S.E.2d 165 (1972)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1998212798" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad1a24574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Johnson v. Cooper, 234 Ga. App. 753, 507 S.E.2d 559 (1998)</cite.query> (disapproved of <case.history>on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1999084086" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad1a24874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Herr v. Withers, 237 Ga. App. 420, 515 S.E.2d 174 (1999)</cite.query>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea5e2174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2008764063" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad28ca274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Brown, 278 Ga. App. 457, 629 S.E.2d 123 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea5e2274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad328e274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Tate v. State, 264 Ga. 53, 440 S.E.2d 646 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea5e2374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad4887274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Tate v. State, 264 Ga. 53, 56, 440 S.E.2d 646 (1994)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2000084356" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad4887574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Hanson, 243 Ga. App. 532, 532 S.E.2d 715 (2000)</cite.query> (issues of witness credibility reserved for trial court, and appellate court cannot substitute its judgment for that of the trial judge); see also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1997238114" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad4887874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Aguirre, 229 Ga. App. 736, 494 S.E.2d 576 (1997)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2004700557" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad4887b74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Hester, 268 Ga. App. 501, 504, 602 S.E.2d 271 (2004)</cite.query> (“Under the controlling precedent from our Supreme Court, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad4887e74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Tate v. State</ital></cite.query>, the trier of fact <begin.quote ID="QT_0006"/>‘is not obligated to believe a witness even if the testimony is uncontradicted and may accept or reject any portion of the testimony.’<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0006"/>”).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea853074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad524b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Tate v. State, 264 Ga. 53, 56 n.5, 440 S.E.2d 646 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea853174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad5e80274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Tate v. State, 264 Ga. 53, 59, 440 S.E.2d 646 (1994)</cite.query> (Carley, J., dissenting).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea853274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2004700557" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad6844274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Hester, 268 Ga. App. 501, 505, 602 S.E.2d 271 (2004)</cite.query> (quoting <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1963125913" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad6844574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sellers v. State, 107 Ga. App. 516, 519, 130 S.E.2d 790 (1963)</cite.query> (emphasis in original)).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea853374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2004700557" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad76ea274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Hester, 268 Ga. App. 501, 505, 602 S.E.2d 271 (2004)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7bea853474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1994057716" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad831f274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Tate v. State, 264 Ga. 53, 440 S.E.2d 646 (1994)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2004700557" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad831f574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Hester, 268 Ga. App. 501, 505, 602 S.E.2d 271 (2004)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2008764063" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad831f874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><?page no="463"?>State v. Brown, 278 Ga. App. 457, 629 S.E.2d 123 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7beaac4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2004700557" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad8a72274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Hester, 268 Ga. App. 501, 505 n.13, 602 S.E.2d 271 (2004)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7beaac4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1950104855" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad91c5274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Pantone v. Pantone, 206 Ga. 305, 57 S.E.2d 77 (1950)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1955105164" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad91c5574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hayes v. Hay, 92 Ga. App. 88, 88 S.E.2d 306 (1955)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See also e.g., <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1999245861" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3ad9dfa274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gatefield Corp. v. Gwinnett County, 240 Ga. App. 847, 847, 524 S.E.2d 553 (1999)</cite.query> (<begin.quote ID="QT_0007"/>“[S]ince we cannot say that Smith&apos;s testimony was without possibility of bias or fault, we find that Gatefield has misplaced reliance on the rule that direct and positive testimony, which is not incredible, impossible, or inherently improbable, must not be arbitrarily rejected by a finder of fact.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0007"/>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7beaac4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="1979138678" w-seq-number="00038" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3adaa2f274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Wilson v. Professional Ins. Corp., 151 Ga. App. 712, 261 S.E.2d 450 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7beaac4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2040553990" w-seq-number="00039" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3adb664274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Walsh, 339 Ga. App. 894, 795 S.E.2d 202 (2016)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d on other grounds</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2043943580" w-seq-number="00040" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3adb664574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">303 Ga. 276, 811 S.E.2d 353 (2018)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017252" w-serial-number="2045714704" w-seq-number="00041" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I3adb664874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Holland v. State, 347 Ga. App. 601, 820 S.E.2d 442 (2018)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 13:8<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
